stmorland, England, United Kingdom","Beetham Castle, Westmorland, England":"Beetham, Westmorland, England","Beetham Castle, Beetham, Cumbria, England":"Beetham, Cumbria, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Emma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   containing the word <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular."],"variants":[]},{"name":"le","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Lewis   or respelling of   Lou  , as borne by the impresario  Lew Grade  (  1906–98 , originally  Louis Winogradsky )."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Fleming","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: ethnic name for someone from Flanders, from Middle English <i>fleming</i>. The word reflects a Norman French form of Old French <i>flamanc</i> ‘Fleming’, from the stem <i>flam-</i> + the ancient Germanic suffix <i>-ing</i>. In the Middle Ages there was considerable commercial intercourse between England and the Netherlands, particularly in the wool trade, and many Flemish weavers and dyers settled in England. This surname is also common in south and east Scotland and in Ireland, where it is sometimes found in the Gaelicized form <b>Pléamonn</b>.","German: variant of   Flemming  , cognate with 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Flemings","meanings":["English: plural form of   Fleming  .","Americanized form of Flemish <b>Vleminckx</b>: patronymic from <b>Vleminck</b>, an ethnic name for someone from Flanders, Middle Dutch <i>vleminc</i>."]},{"name":"Flanders","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, an altered form of <i>Flanders</i>, which originally denoted someone who came to England from that region. Its occasional use as a given name is probably in honour of the explorer  Matthew Flinders  (  1774–1814 ).  Flinders Petrie  (  1853–1942 ) was a famous British archaeologist."]},{"name":"Fleeman","meanings":["English: variant of   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Flemming","meanings":["German: ethnic name for someone from Flanders, Middle High German <i>vlaeminc</i>. People from Flanders spread throughout Germany, as well as England, in the Middle Ages as clothmakers and dyers.","English: variant of   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Flamenco","meanings":["Spanish: ethnic name from <i>flamenco</i> ‘Fleming, Flemish person’ (see   Fleming  )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":9,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":40,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":65,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":78,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Emma le Fleming was born in 1250, in Beetham, Westmorland, England as the daughter of Sir John le Fleming. She married Thomas de Betham I about 1272, in Betham, Somerset, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 2 daughters. She died in 1334, in Westmorland, England, at the age of 84."},"et":{"1250–1334":"1250–1334","1238–Male":"1238–Surnud","1272–Male":"1272–Surnud","1324–Male":"1324–Surnud","1326–Female":"1326–Surnud","1328–Female":"1328–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","about 1272":"umbes 1272","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1326":"1326","1238":"1238","       1326":"1326","1259":"1259","1324":"1324","1334":"1334","       1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1328":"1328","Betham Castle,,Westmorland,England":"Betham, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Westmorland, England":"Westmorland, England","betham castle, Westmorland, England":"Westmorland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Beetham Castle, Westmorland, England":"Beetham, Westmorland, England","Beetham Castle, Beetham, Cumbria, England":"Beetham, Cumbria, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1250–1334":"1250–1334","1238–Male":"1238–Kuollut","1272–Male":"1272–Kuollut","1324–Male":"1324–Kuollut","1326–Female":"1326–Kuollut","1328–Female":"1328–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","about 1272":"noin 1272","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1326":"1326","1238":"1238","       1326":"1326","1259":"1259","1324":"1324","1334":"1334","       1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1328":"1328","Betham Castle,,Westmorland,England":"Betham, Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Engla